{
  "answer": "**The *Kalpabuddha* (a short Medieval Kawi prose work in 6 chapters) does not describe the ten bhūmis (stages) of the bodhisattva path anywhere in the text.** \n\nThis tantric work focuses instead on the five Tathāgatas (Vairocana, Akṣobhya, Ratnasambhava, Amitābha, and Amoghasiddhi), their attributes (colors, directions, consorts/devīs, mantras, mudrās, jñānas, implements, mounts, heavens, and bodily abodes), and their relation to the five wisdoms/senses forming the \"Divine Five-Souls\" (*Pañcātma*). Searches for terms like \"bhūmi(s)\", \"bodhisattva\", \"ten stages\", or \"ten bhumis\" across the corpus (including this work) yielded no matches, and a full reading of all chapters confirms the absence of any such description. The ten bhūmis are a standard Mahāyāna topic (e.g., from the *Daśabhūmika* chapter of the *Avataṃsaka Sūtra*), but they are not covered here.",
